When carrying out Arti fi cial Intelligence-driven Processing operations, Humanitarian Organizations may rely on one or more of the following legal bases: 36

- the vital interest of the Data Subject or of another person;
- the public interest, in particular based on an Organization ' s mandate under national or international law;
- the informed Consent of the Data Subject;
- a legitimate interest of the organization;
- the performance of a contract;
- compliance with a legal obligation.

However, the speci fi c nature of Arti fi cial Intelligence applications and related data Processing poses some challenges to this traditional framework, mainly in the case of individual Consent to data Processing and secondary use of collected data (i.e. data originally collected for a speci fi c purpose and then reused for a different one, as is often the case in Arti fi cial Intelligence given the large-scale data sets needed).

As pointed out in literature, the effectiveness of Data Subjects ' Consent as a legal basis has been weakened by lengthy and technical data Processing notices, social and technical lock-ins, obscure interface design, and lack of awareness on the part of the Data Subject. 37 These developments are even more relevant in the context of

